text: 7.1.5 Gang Phase Implementation: PTOF(sub)new = PTOF(sub)old + gang phase offset. Q: I presume that once this operation is done, PTOF old becomes PTOF new. So if I type in a gang phase of -2, I would get a -2 two degree change. Then if I type in -4, I would have accumulated -6 degrees of change. In this scheme all requested gang phase offset changes would be implemented in a relative sense, and the absolute value of the gang phase offset loses any meaning about where RF crest is. 7.2.2.1 Mode of Operation: "Three modes of operation for each LINAC section..." Q: I trust this language means that different LINAC section can operate in a different modes, as opposed to all being in the same mode. I would use language "Three modes of operation (possibly separate) for each LINAC section..." 7.2.2.4 and 7.2.2.5 "Desired Energy and Chirp Gains": There is discussion about EMAX and CMAX for each LINAC section. What I see as funny here is that CMAX depends upon EDES and vice versa. Stated differently, for a fixed amount of cavity RF available, EMAX can be expressed of as a function of CDES (or vice versa). Maybe I am missing something here, but it seems to me that if EDES is above EMAX, then CDES must also be above CMAX...need to think more about that. I think a better way to approach this might be to calculate EMAX based upon the present CDES, and if that rails set the out of headroom PV. Certainly for operation, if we for whatever reason wind up asking for an inappropriately large CDES (which happens a lot with the copper LINAC), we very rapidly find ourselves with a EMAX which is insufficient to maintain the beam energy. If we cannot regulate both energy and compression, it is always better to back off on the compression (CDES...leaving the bunchlength unregulated) and get energy into regulation. As with the copper LINAC, we will probably wind up having to do that manually when things get out of whack.
